“When a cow is ready to be milked, she’ll walk over to the machine and enter a small enclosure, where she’s treated to a snack of grains. First, lasers and a camera map each cow’s udder — the machine retains this information for easier connections for subsequent milkings. Then, the robotic arm attaches the milking cups to each teat. Before and after the process, the cow’s udder is treated with iodine for sanitation.”

@travelandleisure recently shared an article about Rogue River Blue being served at 36,000 feet on Singapore Airlines – and dove into the sustainability of Rogue’s self-milking cows. The ladies are milked on their own terms, at whatever time of day best suits their habits (the cows naturally want to be milked anywhere from three to six times per day), while the system monitors their health and well-being.

We’re overjoyed to announce that not one, but TWO of our cheeses were selected as finalists for the 2023 Good Food Awards! 🎉🥳🎊

Our Smokey Blue and Caveman Blue cheeses were judged based on craftsmanship, flavor, and commitment to social and environmental responsibility. We are honored to share this victory alongside other top food producers awarded! 

About our award winners: 
⭐️ Smokey Blue is cold-smoked for many hours over Oregon Hazelnut shells. This process infuses infuses the cheese with unique aromas of barrel-aged vanilla, bread pudding, and candied bacon.

⭐️ The natural rind of Caveman Blue allows this cheese to release moisture while cave-aging, developing a fudgy, creamy texture with earthy notes of shiitake mushroom, sweet golden beets, and moderate “blue” flavor.

Have you ever wondered what we do with all of the 🐄💩 ? Well the short answer is that the waste doesn’t go to waste. Our Dairy waste repurposing system separates solid from liquid waste and converts both into usable byproducts. Solid, undigested plant matter is cured and processed into bedding that we use in the stalls of the Cow Palace. We also sell it by the truckload to local farmers for use as soil amendment - great for adding nutrients and breaking up the thick, clay-heavy soil types that are common in Southern Oregon. We even repurpose our liquid manure, spraying it as an organic fertilizer in our pastures!

Happy #MooMonday! As we continue our deep-dive into amazing anatomy of cows, today we’re spotlighting a feature that’s both functional and fantastic - the cow’s hoof! 🐮

Much like the tire of a car, a cow’s hoof is designed for durability, bearing the weight of these hefty beauties while navigating varying terrains.

But there’s more than what meets the eye! The hoof is also a critical part of a cow’s circulatory system. As cows move, their hooves use a blood pumping mechanism that pumps blood back to the heart!

So, the next time you see a cow sauntering along, remember that those four hooves are working hard at not only supporting our bovine friends, but playing a crucial role in keeping them healthy.

Stay tuned for more cow-facts as we explore the world of our cheesemaking companions each week.

What are our fabulous cheesemakers doing? They’re cutting the cheese!!! Or the curd, to be more precise 😅. Around 30 minutes after a coagulant is added to the milk, the curd is cut into small pieces. Then, the curds continue to firm up and release the whey. About an hour after the whey is drained, the curds are ready to be salted, and put into hoops that help shape the round loaves that we see in the final product!

HAY there! What are those giant green pillows in our pasture? That’s hay made from our organic pasture grasses. After letting our pasture grow out long and thick, we mow it and let it dry for 1-2 days. Then, we wrap the hay in a protective plastic, preserving its protein content and enabling us to store it throughout the winter. Think of it as our version of canning! With each harvest, we produce anywhere between 400-600 bales of hay. We take pride in feeding our girls with the goodness we grow right here on the farm. 🌱🐄

We want to share with you that David Gremmels has retired from Rogue Creamery. “I am confident his legacy in cheese will be remembered for generations. David risked everything in 2002 to save a small creamery, Rogue River Valley Creamery, from closure by purchasing it and creating numerous original American cheeses,” says Pierre Ragnet, Deputy Director Savencia Group and Chairman of Rogue Creamery. “Savencia Group and Rogue Creamery are thankful for David’s valuable contributions to the community, environment and cheese industry.”
 
One of David’s recipes, Rogue River Blue, took the world by surprise and was crowned Best of Show out of 3800 cheeses from 42 countries at the 2019 World Cheese Awards – a first for American Cheese. Another first was exporting Rogue Creamery cheese in 2008 under a newly granted USDA raw milk cheese export certificate. David's passion for sustainable and organic agriculture led him to incorporate Rogue Creamery as Oregon's first B-corporation in 2013. Rogue Creamery has ranked in the top 5% of B-Corps worldwide under David’s leadership. He founded the Oregon Cheese Festival in 2003 and Oregon Cheese Guild in 2006. In 2022, David was honored with the American Cheese Society Lifetime Achievement Award and Oregon State University's College of Agriculture’s Hall of Fame Award.
 
David credits Rogue Creamery successes to its team and stakeholders. His title remains Master Caseiculturalist. He will continue to enjoy his passions of organic agriculture and volunteering for Oregon State University's Food Science, Technology and Engineering Advisory Board, the American Cheese Society, Oregon Tourism Commission and the Governor's Sustainability Board. David expressed that he, “wishes the Savencia Fromage and Dairy and the Rogue Creamery teams well as they continue to consciously steward Rogue Creamery and its mission forward into the next generation.” Rogue Creamery’s mission is: People dedicated to sustainability, service and the art and tradition of creating the world’s finest hand-made cheese.
 
“We wish David well professionally and personally.” said Juan Carlos Dalto, CEO Savencia Fromage and Dairy, Americas.

Happy #MooMonday! We’re back again with our series about the wonders of cow anatomy. Today, we’re all ears - literally! We’re exploring the wonders of cow ears. 🐮

Beyond being simply endEARing, a cow’s ears are a marvel of nature. They have an extraordinary ability to rotate allowing them to capture sounds from all directions. This gives our girls an incredible sense of spatial awareness, making sure they’re always in tune with their surroundings.

But that’s not all - the position of a cow’s ears can even tell us about how she’s feeling. If her ears are upright or forwards, she is alert and paying attention. If her ears are back or hanging, she is relaxed and content! 

Join us next week as we continue to delve deeper into the fascinating world of these gentle giants! 🐄

Happy National Moldy Cheese Day! 🎉 

For those new to their cheese journeys, here’s a fun fact: blue veins and coloration in blue cheese is caused by - yes, you guessed it - mold! There are several strains of mold that are used in the crafting of blue cheese, and we use penicillium roqueforti - the classic fungus that has been used in Roquefort, France for centuries.

In 1954, Rogue Creamery first crafted Oregon Blue Vein Cheese (now simply “Oregon Blue”), one of the West Coast’s very first French-style, cave-aged blue cheeses. Fast forward to today: our tradition of making deliciously moldy masterpieces continues to delight cheese lovers worldwide. 💙🧀

At last week’s World Cheese Awards, a Norwegian blue named Nidelven Blå took top honors – but our blue cheeses received important accolades, too! Caveman Blue and Bluehorn Blue both won Silver medals, while Oregon Blue and Smokey Blue each took home a Bronze.
 
Our aged hard cheeses were also well-received, with Reserve Touvelle winning Silver and Cheese Is Love Extra-Aged Cheddar, Bronze.
 
You can find these and more award-winning cheeses at RogueCreamery.com!
 
About the World Cheese Awards:
Organized by the @guildoffinefood, the World Cheese Awards is a truly global cheese event. Now in its 35th edition, this competition brings together cheesemakers, retailers, buyers and food commentators worldwide to judge over 4,000 cheeses from over 40 countries. This year’s World Cheese Awards took place in Trondheim, Norway.
 
Wondering why Rogue River Blue wasn’t honored this year? We retired our World Champion from this competition following its win in 2019 to allow our other cheeses the chance to take the spotlight!

We’re celebrating the journey from pasture to plate this #MooMonday! Our dairy queens play a vital role in our cheesemaking process, and it all begins with their nourishing diet of our own organic pasture grasses. 🐄🌿

Starting last year we began producing our own hay from our pastures to ensure a close-looped system on our farm, and to store during the colder months. Exceptional cheese starts with happy cows enjoying the very best grass, and what’s better than our own? This is yet another way our cheeses are infused with the unique flavors of our region that you can taste in every bite. 💙
